06324nam a22007095i 9780822376439DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223764397 a10.1515/97808223764392doi  a(DE-B1597)552043  a(OCoLC)873034784  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a301.0104aThe Ground Between :bAnthropologists Engage Philosophy /ced. by Michael Jackson, Veena Das, Arthur Kleinman, Bhrigupati Singh. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b2 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Experiments between Anthropology and Philosophy: Affinities and Antagonisms -- t1. Ajàlá’s Heads: Refl ections on Anthropology and Philosophy in a West African Setting -- t2. The Parallel Lives of Philosophy and Anthropology, -- t3. Th e Difficulty of Kindness: Boundaries, Time, and the Ordinary -- t4. Ethnography in the Way of Theory -- t5. The Search for Wisdom: Why William James Still Matter -- t6. Eavesdropping on Bourdieu’s Philosophers -- t7. How Concepts Make the World Look Different: Affirmative and Negative Genealogies of Th ought -- t8. Philosophia and Anthropologia: Reading alongside Benjamin in Yazd, Derrida in Qum, Arendt in Tehran -- t9. Ritual Disjunctions: Ghosts, Philosophy, and Anthropology -- t10. Henri Bergson in Highland Yemen -- t11. Must We Be Bad Epistemologists? Illusions of Transparency, the Opaque Other, and Interpretive Foibles -- t12. Action, Expression, and Everyday Life: Recounting House hold Events -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe guiding inspiration of this book is the attraction and distance that mark the relation between anthropology and philosophy. This theme is explored through encounters between individual anthropologists and particular regions of philosophy. Several of the most basic concepts of the discipline—including notions of ethics, politics, temporality, self and other, and the nature of human life—are products of a dialogue, both implicit and explicit, between anthropology and philosophy. These philosophical undercurrents in anthropology also speak to the question of what it is to experience our being in a world marked by radical difference and otherness. In The Ground Between, twelve leading anthropologists offer intimate reflections on the influence of particular philosophers on their way of seeing the world, and on what ethnography has taught them about philosophy. Ethnographies of the mundane and the everyday raise fundamental issues that the contributors grapple with in both their lives and their thinking. With directness and honesty, they relate particular philosophers to matters such as how to respond to the suffering of the other, how concepts arise in the give and take of everyday life, and how to be attuned to the world through the senses. Their essays challenge the idea that philosophy is solely the province of professional philosophers, and suggest that certain modalities of being in the world might be construed as ways of doing philosophy.Contributors. João Biehl, Steven C. Caton, Vincent Crapanzano, Veena Das, Didier Fassin, Michael M. J. Fischer, Ghassan Hage, Clara Han, Michael Jackson, Arthur Kleinman, Michael Puett, Bhrigupati Singh  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBiehl, João, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaton, Steven C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrapanzano, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb